				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${{{{\mathrm{ln}}}}}(\Delta \;{{{{{\rm{incidence}}}}}}\,{{{{{\rm{rate}}}}}}+1)$$\end{document}ln(Δincidencerate+1)), i.e., the difference between the observed start-of-week and end-of-week cumulative incidence rates, during the four-weekly temporal lags (t-1,…,t-4), as another set of features in all of our models (category C.ii) (since cumulative rates are used, the “change” will always be greater than zero). These features conceptually capture the Infected compartment in the SIR model, i.e., the currently infected populations in the spatial unit. Our autoregressive modeling with multiple temporal lags allows the models to learn the rate of spread in a unit, as well as the varying incubation periods of the disease in relation to the change in temperature and demographic features48,49.

